<<main_headline>>
<m0>After 25 years, visionary's ideal community,<ql>
an antidote to suburban sprawl, hangs on.<ql>
Citizens are few, but the dream unflagging.<ql>
<m1><ue5><m2><ql>
<m1><styl>cxoff<ql>
<m1><styl>ruleron<ql>
<styl>jump,13.7i,1<ql>
1G<ue5>3G<ue5>UTOPIA<ql>
<styl>txt,12p2<ql>
<styl>capline,3<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0> Most of us complain about where we live. Suburbs sprawl, downtowns decay, a sense of community is lost. Today, a few people are trying to build something completely different: <m1> <m0>utopia. This story is the second in a three-part series about communities that challenge the way the rest of us live.<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,6<ql>
<styl>by <m0>By PETER WHORISKEY<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Architecture Writer<ep>
   <m2><ql>
<ql>
<m0>U<m2><ql>
<m0>p out of Phoenix the tourists come, careening rental cars on the desert highway, past the outer rings of suburbia, past the subdivisions and car lots and fast-food drive-thrus, until finally the landscape is nothing but blazing expanses of saguaro cacti, red rock ledges and dry river beds.<ep>
   They're headed for Arcosanti, an urban experiment that guidebooks describe as ``a post-apocalypse city'' and ``a futuristic vision.'' The brief descriptions set the tourists in a state of high anticipation (--) for who has not wondered if there is a better way? (--) but hardly prepare them for what follows.<ep>
   It's an hour ride until the Arcosanti exit pops into view, the cars shimmy over a bumpy dirt road, and the tires crackle to a stop. The visitors step dazed and dead-legged into<m0> . . . terra incognita<m0>.<ep>
<m0>   Looks like ancient ruins<ep>
<m0>    What they find is a clump of odd concrete buildings, with circular windows, half domes and decorations as primitive as cave scrawlings, that looks at first like the ruins of some ancient desert tribe.<ep>
   But the visitors also spot a few scruffy people (--) beards, jeans, boots (--) shuffling between buildings, tinkering in a metal foundry, improvising with solar engineering; and so in fact, Arcosanti is alive, and in its half-modern-half-Stone-Age aura it could double as one of the cities from the Mad Max movies.<ep>
   What is strangest about Arcosanti, however, and what undoubtedly limits its success as a tourist attraction, is that the 25-year-old community is founded on a critical premise: that the American dream, the national ideal of a big house on a big lot, is gobbling up natural habitat and leading us to ecological catastrophe. It's a small world after all.<ep>
<m0>   Density of New York City<ep>
<m0>   Now home to about 50 people, mainly young single men, Arcosanti is envisioned as the antithesis of suburban sprawl. Very, <m0>very<m0> slowly (--) because they are always strapped for cash (--) the residents are building a hyper-dense cluster of energy-efficient towers, a village for 7,000 people fitting on just 20 acres. The population density would approach that of New York. By limiting the human habitat (--) the city grows up, not out (--) thousands of desert acres around the town can be preserved.<ep>
   ``Suburbia can't keep on spreading out over the planet,'' a bearded Arcosanti guide assures the arriving tourists. ``We just <m0>can't<m0> afford to do that.''<ep>
   The $5 tour also reveals that the 50 or more year-round resi<m2><ql>
<ql>
